The paper deals with the problem of interference minimization in wireless ad hoc networks, which is a topic in the field of computer networks. Specifically, it focuses on the modeling and optimization of interference in wireless networks with randomly positioned nodes. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category. 

The paper also involves the use of algorithms and data structures to solve the interference minimization problem, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. 

Furthermore, the paper discusses the use of probability distributions and statistical analysis to analyze the performance of the proposed algorithm, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-categories. 

Finally, the paper presents a local algorithm that constructs a graph with an upper bound on the expected maximum interference, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) sub-category.
